{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":208,"record_hash":"sha256:493479d4dfeb675019b263a54ff9b58f86df38fbe381fe5a83be991c7aa62cd0","timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:19:17.611Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I’d extend GitMeta atomic edits. Constraining the model to list/set just to fit today’s API is the wrong kind of clever.\n\nWhat to consider:\n\n**The failure mode is real**\nRight now `but-agentlog` does this in separate writes:\n\n```text\nset session metadata\nset source metadata\napply_edits(transcript list + record hash set)\n```\n\nFor turns, if we do:\n\n```text\nappend transcript records\nadd record hashes\nwrite turn summary\nwrite turn detail\nwrite indexes\n```\n\nand only some of that lands, retries get weird. The nastiest case is:\n\n```text\ntranscript records + record hashes succeed\nturn write fails\nretry sees 0 new records\nno turn is created\n```\n\nNow the transcript exists, but the capture boundary is gone forever unless we add repair logic.\n\n**List/set-only storage is possible, but ugly**\nWe could store turn detail as a list entry instead of scalar record:\n\n```text\n:turns = list<TurnDetail JSON>\n```\n\nThen one `apply_edits` can append transcript records, add hashes, append turn detail, and add index set memberships.\n\nThat avoids extending GitMeta, but it has costs:\n\n- reading one turn by key becomes scan-the-list\n- replacing/rebuilding a turn detail is awkward\n- dedupe/idempotency for turn list entries is worse than set/scalar keys\n- `TurnSummary` vs `TurnDetail` becomes fake separation\n- the storage shape is driven by GitMeta limitations, not the domain\n\nFor a tiny POC, it works. For something we expect to query by turn, it ages badly.\n\n**Extending GitMeta is cleaner**\nAdd `MetaEdit` variants like:\n\n```rust\nSet { key, value }\nRemove { key }\n```\n\nMaybe later:\n\n```rust\nSetRecord { prefix, record }\n```\n\nThen `but-agentlog` can write a coherent batch:\n\n```text\nset session schema / updated-at\nset source fields\nappend transcript records\nadd record hashes\nappend turn summary\nset turn detail\nadd index memberships\n```\n\nThat matches the model we actually want:\n\n```text\n:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\n:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n:index:* = set<session-key/turn-key>\n```\n\n**The bigger GitMeta question**\nBefore extending it, we should check whether GitMeta’s transaction semantics are truly target-local and all-or-nothing across mixed value types. The existing `apply_edits` says “if any edit fails, none of the batch is committed,” but only for list/set edits. If scalar values go through the same store transaction path, this is probably straightforward. If scalar writes have different merge/tombstone behavior, we need to be careful.\n\n**My recommendation**\nExtend GitMeta atomic edits now, with only the smallest useful surface:\n\n```text\nMetaEdit::SetValue { key, value }\nMetaEdit::ListAppend { ... }\nMetaEdit::SetAdd { ... }\n```\n\nDon’t add a fancy record abstraction yet. `but-agentlog` can serialize `TurnDetail` as a JSON string and set it at `gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key>`.\n\nThat keeps the agentlog model sane and avoids baking repair logic into v1.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:19:17.611Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}